org/2000/svg" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" width="401.6666666666667" height="281.6666666666667"><g class="hoverlayer"></g></svg></div></div></div></foreignObject></g><g transform="translate(327,17)" x="327" y="17" title="codeHTML" width="398" height="671" class="codeHTML" name="codeHTML" rot="0"><foreignObject x="0" y="0" width="222" height="200" style="height: 671px; width: 663.333px;"><div name="htmlCode" style="zoom: 60%; height: 671px; width: 663.333px;" code="<div class=&quot;ch&quot;>
    
    <h1>BJT Transistor Output Characteristics - DC Sweep Analysis</h1>

    <div class=&quot;ch-card&quot;>
        <h2>Circuit Components</h2>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>Q1:</strong> 2N2222 NPN Transistor</li>
            <li><strong>I1:</strong> DC Current Source = 10 mA (base current Ib)</li>
            <li><strong>Vce:</strong> DC Voltage Source = 10V (collector-emitter voltage)</li>
            <li><strong>Analysis Type:</strong> DC Sweep of Vce</li>
            <li><strong>Output:</strong> I(Q1.c) - Collector current</li>
        </ul>
    </div>

    <h2>DC Sweep Parameters</h2>
    <div class=&quot;ch-formula&quot;>
        Parameter: Vce<br>
        Start: 0V<br>
        Step: 0.1V<br>
        Stop: 8V<br>
        Total Points: 81
    </div>

    <h2>Current Gain Calculation</h2>
    <div class=&quot;ch-formula&quot;>
        β (hFE) = Ic / Ib = 0.85A / 10mA ≈ <strong>85</strong><br>
        This is the DC current gain of the 2N2222 transistor
    </div>

    <h2>Simulation Results</h2>
    <div class=&quot;ch-grid&quot;>

        <div class=&quot;ch-col blue&quot;>
            <h3>Saturation Region (Vce < 1V)</h3>
            <ul>
                <li>Collector current rises rapidly from 0 to ~0.85A</li>
                <li>Both base-emitter and base-collector junctions are forward-biased</li>
                <li>Transistor acts like a closed switch</li>
                <li>Vce(sat) ≈ 0.2V (typical for 2N2222)</li>
                <li>Ic is strongly dependent on Vce in this region</li>
            </ul>
        </div>

        <div class=&quot;ch-col red&quot;>
            <h3>Active Region (Vce > 1V)</h3>
            <ul>
                <li>Collector current stabilizes at ~0.85A</li>
                <li>Base-emitter junction forward-biased, base-collector reverse-biased</li>
                <li>Ic ≈ β × Ib (current controlled by base current)</li>
                <li>Slight positive slope due to Early effect</li>
                <li>Transistor acts as a current amplifier</li>
            </ul>
        </div>

    </div>

    <div class=&quot;ch-card green-border&quot;>
        <h2>Conclusion</h2>
        <p style=&quot;line-height: 1.6; margin: 0;&quot;>This simulation shows the <strong>output characteristics</strong> of a BJT transistor at a fixed base current (Ib = 10mA). The curve clearly displays two distinct operating regions: the <strong>saturation region</strong> at low Vce where the transistor behaves like a closed switch, and the <strong>active region</strong> at higher Vce where the transistor acts as a current amplifier with Ic ≈ β×Ib. The current gain β ≈ 85 is typical for the 2N2222 transistor. The slight upward slope in the active region is due to the Early effect (base-width modulation), which causes Ic to increase slightly with Vce even at constant Ib.</p>
    </div>

    <div class=&quot;ch-card&quot; style=&quot;background-color: #e8f8f5; border-left: 4px solid #1abc9c;&quot;>
        <h2 style=&quot;color: #16a085;&quot;>Transistor Operating Regions Summary</h2>
        <ul style=&quot;line-height: 1.6; margin: 0;&quot;>
            <li><strong>Cutoff:</strong> Ib = 0, Ic ≈ 0 (transistor OFF)</li>
            <li><strong>Saturation:</strong> Vce < Vce(sat), both junctions forward-biased, acts as switch ON</li>
            <li><strong>Active:</strong> Vce > Vce(sat), used for amplification, Ic = β×Ib</li>
            <li><strong>Early Voltage:</strong> Determines the slope in active region (output resistance)</li>
            <li><strong>Applications:</strong> Amplifiers (active region), switches (saturation/cutoff)</li>
        </ul>
    </div>

</div>"><div class="ch">
    
    <h1>BJT Transistor Output Characteristics - DC Sweep Analysis</h1>

    <div class="ch-card">
        <h2>Circuit Components</h2>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>Q1:</strong> 2N2222 NPN Transistor</li>
            <li><strong>I1:</strong> DC Current Source = 10 mA (base current Ib)</li>
            <li><strong>Vce:</strong> DC Voltage Source = 10V (collector-emitter voltage)</li>
            <li><strong>Analysis Type:</strong> DC Sweep of Vce</li>
            <li><strong>Output:</strong> I(Q1.c) - Collector current</li>
        </ul>
    </div>

    <h2>DC Sweep Parameters</h2>
    <div class="ch-formula">
        Parameter: Vce<br>
        Start: 0V<br>
        Step: 0.1V<br>
        Stop: 8V<br>
        Total Points: 81
    </div>

    <h2>Current Gain Calculation</h2>
    <div class="ch-formula">
        β (hFE) = Ic / Ib = 0.85A / 10mA ≈ <strong>85</strong><br>
        This is the DC current gain of the 2N2222 transistor
    </div>

    <h2>Simulation Results</h2>
    <div class="ch-grid">

        <div class="ch-col blue">
            <h3>Saturation Region (Vce &lt; 1V)</h3>
            <ul>
                <li>Collector current rises rapidly from 0 to ~0.85A</li>
                <li>Both base-emitter and base-collector junctions are forward-biased</li>
                <li>Transistor acts like a closed switch</li>
                <li>Vce(sat) ≈ 0.2V (typical for 2N2222)</li>
                <li>Ic is strongly dependent on Vce in this region</li>
            </ul>
        </div>

        <div class="ch-col red">
            <h3>Active Region (Vce &gt; 1V)</h3>
            <ul>
                <li>Collector current stabilizes at ~0.85A</li>
                <li>Base-emitter junction forward-biased, base-collector reverse-biased</li>
                <li>Ic ≈ β × Ib (current controlled by base current)</li>
                <li>Slight positive slope due to Early effect</li>
                <li>Transistor acts as a current amplifier</li>
            </ul>
        </div>

    </div>

    <div class="ch-card green-border">
        <h2>Conclusion</h2>
        <p style="line-height: 1.6; margin: 0;">This simulation shows the <strong>output characteristics</strong> of a BJT transistor at a fixed base current (Ib = 10mA). The curve clearly displays two distinct operating regions: the <strong>saturation region</strong> at low Vce where the transistor behaves like a closed switch, and the <strong>active region</strong> at higher Vce where the transistor acts as a current amplifier with Ic ≈ β×Ib. The current gain β ≈ 85 is typical for the 2N2222 transistor. The slight upward slope in the active region is due to the Early effect (base-width modulation), which causes Ic to increase slightly with Vce even at constant Ib.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="ch-card" style="background-color: #e8f8f5; border-left: 4px solid #1abc9c;">
        <h2 style="color: #16a085;">Transistor Operating Regions Summary</h2>
        <ul style="line-height: 1.6; margin: 0;">
            <li><strong>Cutoff:</strong> Ib = 0, Ic ≈ 0 (transistor OFF)</li>
            <li><strong>Saturation:</strong> Vce &lt; Vce(sat), both junctions forward-biased, acts as switch ON</li>
            <li><strong>Active:</strong> Vce &gt; Vce(sat), used for amplification, Ic = β×Ib</li>
            <li><strong>Early Voltage:</strong> Determines the slope in active region (output resistance)</li>
            <li><strong>Applications:</strong> Amplifiers (active region), switches (saturation/cutoff)</li>
        </ul>
    </div>

</div></div></foreignObject></g>